<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,537,332,357]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Comparisons and Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[546,755,333,356]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrops">
<emphasis box="[546,755,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Epigonus macrops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in the genus in having a ventral luminous organ; one of the eight pyloric caeca appears to have become modified into this organ. The luminescent window is located mid-ventrally between the anterior part of the pelvic-fins and is covered by a single large scale (see 
<bibRefCitation box="[1291,1432,404,429]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref20071" refString="Mayer, G. F. (1974) A revision of the cardinalfish genus Epigonus (Perciformes, Apogonidae), with descriptions of two new species. Bulletin Museum of Comparative Zoology, 146, 147 - 203." type="journal article">Mayer 1974</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 7; Okamoto 
<emphasis box="[336,386,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">et al</emphasis>
. 2012: fig. 3). Also, the eighth dorsal-fin spine is isolated between the first and second dorsal fins or, rarely, is connected by a membrane to the seventh spine of the first dorsal fin (expressed as VII-I-I, 10 or 
<collectionCode box="[151,221,512,535]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">VIII-I</collectionCode>
, 10). This feature is shared with only four other species in the genus and is known as a unique diagnostic character for the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1810" box="[348,499,548,572]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="telescopus">
<emphasis box="[348,499,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">E. telescopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<bibRefCitation box="[590,781,548,573]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref21172" refString="Okamoto, M. (2016 b) Epigonidae. In: Matsuura, K. &amp; Hoshino, K. (Eds.), Fishes Collected from the Western South Indian Ocean. Marine Fisheries Research and Development Center, Fisheries Research Agency, Yokohama, pp. 74 - 77." type="book chapter">Okamoto 2016b</bibRefCitation>
). Although several authors reported 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[1200,1328,549,572]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrops">
<emphasis box="[1200,1328,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">E. macrops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the east coast of Africa (
<bibRefCitation box="[387,529,584,608]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref20071" refString="Mayer, G. F. (1974) A revision of the cardinalfish genus Epigonus (Perciformes, Apogonidae), with descriptions of two new species. Bulletin Museum of Comparative Zoology, 146, 147 - 203." type="journal article">Mayer 1974</bibRefCitation>
; Shchelbachev 1987; 
<bibRefCitation box="[777,951,583,608]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref17192" refString="Abramov, A. A. (1992) Species composition and distribution of Epigonus (Epigonidae) in the world ocean. Journal of Ichthyology, 32, 94 - 108." type="journal article">Abramov 1992</bibRefCitation>
), these authors did not provide any data of the examined specimens (spots of the species in 
<figureCitation box="[727,797,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[376,1217,1316,1962]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[346,1242,1316,1975]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution of four species of the Epigonus oligolepis group and the E. telescopus group in the Western Indian Ocean." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1182169/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
based on their studies). We thus did not examine any specimens from the 
<collectingRegion box="[377,468,656,679]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Western" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Western</collectingRegion>
Indian Ocean area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="278" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[199,410,693,716]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrops">
<emphasis box="[199,410,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Epigonus macrops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described based on two 
<typeStatus box="[878,976,693,717]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">syntypes</typeStatus>
from the eastern Indian Ocean (
<bibRefCitation pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref17837" refString="Brauer, A. (1906) Die Tiefsee-Fische. I. Systematischer Teil. In: Chun, C. (Ed.), Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der Deutschen Tiefsee-Expedition &quot; Valdivia &quot;, 1898 - 99. Vol. 15. Gustav Fischer, Jena, 432 pp., 18 pls." type="book chapter">Brauer 1906</bibRefCitation>
). Although we did examine the larger specimen of these, deposited in the 
<collectionCode box="[1042,1105,728,751]" country="Germany" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/8syf-d21i" name="Museum f�r Naturkunde Berlin (Zoological Collections)" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">ZMB</collectionCode>
, a smaller specimen has been lost.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="278" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">
<taxonomicName authority="McCosker &amp; Long, 1997" authorityName="McCosker &amp; Long" authorityYear="1997" box="[199,691,799,824]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="merleni">
<emphasis box="[199,398,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Epigonus merleni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[406,691,799,824]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref20198" refString="McCosker, J. E. &amp; Long, D. J. (1997) A new species of the deepwater cardinalfish Epigonus (Perciformes: Epigonidae) from the Galapagos Islands. Ichthyological Research, 44, 125 - 129. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 02678691" type="journal article">McCosker &amp; Long, 1997</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described on the basis a single specimen collected from the Galápagos Islands. It was considered to be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[973,1101,837,860]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrops">
<emphasis box="[973,1101,837,860]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">E. macrops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having 11 + 14 Vertebrae and 57 lateral-line scales, but first author’s examination of 
<typeStatus box="[812,910,871,896]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McCosker &amp; Long" authorityYear="1997" box="[948,1064,872,896]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="merleni">
<emphasis box="[948,1064,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">E. merleni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
revealed that it actually has 10 + 15 vertebrae, 48 + 5 lateral-line scales, and a luminescent window near the pelvic-fin base (see Okamoto 
<emphasis box="[1377,1428,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">et al</emphasis>
. 2012). Therefore, they concluded that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McCosker &amp; Long" authorityYear="1997" box="[581,697,944,968]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="merleni">
<emphasis box="[581,697,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">E. merleni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Okamoto et al. 2012)" authorityName="Okamoto et al." authorityYear="2012" box="[963,1349,943,968]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrops">
<emphasis box="[963,1090,945,968]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">E. macrops</emphasis>
(Okamoto 
<emphasis box="[1217,1267,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">et al</emphasis>
. 2012)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
